---
import SiteLayout from "../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
import { siteConfig } from "../site-config";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Install Nodus"
  description="Install Nodus from a clean public URL, crates.io, or Homebrew."
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <span class="eyebrow">Install</span>
    <h1>Install Nodus from a clean public endpoint.</h1>
    <p>
      Use the public installer URLs on this domain, or install from crates.io or Homebrew.
      Release assets still come from GitHub Releases, but the command you share stays stable.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="install-grid">
      <article class="card">
        <h2>macOS and Linux</h2>
        <p class="muted">Downloads the correct release asset for the current OS and architecture.</p>
        <pre><code>{siteConfig.installUnixCommand}</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h2>Windows PowerShell</h2>
        <p class="muted">Use PowerShell 7+ when possible for the smoothest install path.</p>
        <pre><code>{siteConfig.installWindowsCommand}</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h2>crates.io</h2>
        <p class="muted">Install from the Rust ecosystem if you prefer Cargo-managed binaries.</p>
        <pre><code>cargo install nodus</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h2>Homebrew</h2>
        <p class="muted">Uses the prebuilt release archives published by the project.</p>
        <pre><code>brew install nodus-rs/nodus/nodus</code></pre>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="grid-2">
      <article class="card">
        <h2>Pin a version</h2>
        <p class="muted">
          The installer supports a pinned version through <code>NODUS_VERSION</code> on Unix
          and PowerShell.
        </p>
        <pre><code>{`curl -fsSL https://nodus.elata.ai/install.sh | NODUS_VERSION=${siteConfig.latestVersion} bash`}</code></pre>
        <pre><code>{`$env:NODUS_VERSION = "${siteConfig.latestVersion}"\nirm https://nodus.elata.ai/install.ps1 | iex`}</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h2>Checksum verification</h2>
        <p class="muted">
          The Unix installer supports inline verification. On Windows, download the script to a
          temporary path and invoke it with <code>-Verify</code>.
        </p>
        <pre><code>curl -fsSL https://nodus.elata.ai/install.sh | bash -s -- --verify</code></pre>
        <pre><code>{`$script = Join-Path $env:TEMP "nodus-install.ps1"\nirm https://nodus.elata.ai/install.ps1 -OutFile $script\n& $script -Verify\nRemove-Item $script`}</code></pre>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="grid-2">
      <article class="card">
        <h2>What the public installer does</h2>
        <p class="muted">
          It detects the host platform, resolves the release tag, downloads the matching archive,
          optionally verifies the checksum, and installs the binary into a standard user-scoped path.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h2>Raw installer endpoints</h2>
        <p class="muted">
          These routes are published as plain text and are intended to be curl- and PowerShell-friendly.
        </p>
        <div class="tag-row">
          <a class="tag" href="/install.sh">/install.sh</a>
          <a class="tag" href="/install.ps1">/install.ps1</a>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</SiteLayout>
